00:47:04.264 --> 00:47:05.680
AUDIENCE: How are
you doing Steve?

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:06.660
STEVE HINDY: Good.

00:47:06.660 --> 00:47:09.707
AUDIENCE: So craft brewer
myself in Brooklyn,

00:47:09.707 --> 00:47:11.665
Park Slope, backyard,
your old stomping ground.

00:47:11.665 --> 00:47:12.740
STEVE HINDY: Uh-huh.

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:14.376
AUDIENCE: Shoutut to the
Brooklyn [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:14.376 --> 00:47:15.084
It's my favorite.

00:47:15.084 --> 00:47:17.240
I don't know if that's
[INAUDIBLE] Garrett's?

00:47:17.240 --> 00:47:19.206
Quick question, so I'm
actually heading out

00:47:19.206 --> 00:47:21.205
to the Ommegang for their
little camping session

00:47:21.205 --> 00:47:22.220
that they do every year.

00:47:22.220 --> 00:47:24.070
Been going there for years.

00:47:24.070 --> 00:47:27.319
Chimay bought them
out a couple years.

00:47:27.319 --> 00:47:28.610
STEVE HINDY: Not Chimay, Duvel.

00:47:28.610 --> 00:47:29.431
AUDIENCE: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:47:29.431 --> 00:47:29.930
Yes.

00:47:29.930 --> 00:47:31.572
STEVE HINDY: Yeah,
Mort got that.

00:47:31.572 --> 00:47:33.947
AUDIENCE: Right, there's sort
of a trend that's going on.

00:47:33.947 --> 00:47:38.000
The same thing happened with
Goose Island bought out by,

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.654
Budweiser, and they were
bought out by InBev.

00:47:40.654 --> 00:47:41.820
Where do you see that going?

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:43.835
It's almost like a
startup situation

00:47:43.835 --> 00:47:46.285
that we have here where if
you come with a good beer

00:47:46.285 --> 00:47:49.422
you get bought out or you
isolate, keep yourself

00:47:49.422 --> 00:47:52.989
contained, maintain
just to your audience.

00:47:52.989 --> 00:47:54.780
Where do you see the
future as far as that?

00:47:54.780 --> 00:47:57.170
Because I know obviously
these agencies,

00:47:57.170 --> 00:48:01.030
these bigger companies obviously
know the power of craft beer.

00:48:01.030 --> 00:48:04.823
So if they see something, maybe
a spark, do they buy it up?

00:48:04.823 --> 00:48:06.765
And do you get rich quick?

00:48:06.765 --> 00:48:08.010
Just your thoughts on that.

00:48:08.010 --> 00:48:09.250
STEVE HINDY: Yeah.

00:48:09.250 --> 00:48:11.260
Well, I think some
people are going

00:48:11.260 --> 00:48:14.650
to sell, no question about it.

00:48:14.650 --> 00:48:19.590
John Hall from Goose Island
sold to Anheuser-Busch.

00:48:19.590 --> 00:48:23.480
John started the same year
I did, I know him very well,

00:48:23.480 --> 00:48:25.140
he and his son Greg.

00:48:25.140 --> 00:48:28.670
But Greg told his
dad he really didn't

00:48:28.670 --> 00:48:30.490
want to do this for
the rest of his life.

00:48:30.490 --> 00:48:35.390
So John is, at the time he sold,
I think he was 69 years old.

00:48:35.390 --> 00:48:38.090
And what you're going to do?

00:48:38.090 --> 00:48:39.340
He cashed out.

00:48:39.340 --> 00:48:41.370
I have no problem with that.

00:48:43.980 --> 00:48:49.640
I think for the big guys,
craft beer is a real dilemma.

00:48:49.640 --> 00:48:52.070
MillerCoors makes Blue Moon.

00:48:52.070 --> 00:48:54.920
AB has Shock Top, now
they have Goose Island.

00:48:54.920 --> 00:48:59.730
They bought Bluepoint out on
Long Island a couple of months

00:48:59.730 --> 00:49:00.230
ago.

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:08.520
They're going to play in our
segment, no question about it.

00:49:08.520 --> 00:49:11.590
I don't think they can
dominate our segment the way

00:49:11.590 --> 00:49:15.400
they dominated mainstream beer.

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:19.600
Also, I think the more they
play in our segment the more

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:22.180
they undercut their big brands.

00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:25.450
When I started in
business, imports

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:27.940
were 3% of the US market.

00:49:27.940 --> 00:49:30.600
The other 97% was
national brands.

00:49:30.600 --> 00:49:33.570
Today, imports are 13%.

00:49:33.570 --> 00:49:37.770
Craft beer is like
more than 10%,

00:49:37.770 --> 00:49:41.820
and MillerCoors
and InBev are 74%.

00:49:41.820 --> 00:49:48.760
So arguably, we've pushed
them back from 97% to 74%.

00:49:48.760 --> 00:49:51.230
And it's going to
continue, I think.

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:53.460
They're going to
buy craft breweries.

00:49:53.460 --> 00:49:55.670
There's a guy I know
who's on the board,

00:49:55.670 --> 00:49:57.540
I actually I know a
lot of the big brewers

00:49:57.540 --> 00:50:00.510
because I've been on their
board for several years.

00:50:00.510 --> 00:50:06.430
They have one token small guy
on the board, and it's been me.

00:50:06.430 --> 00:50:08.670
One of the guys on the
board of MillerCoors,

00:50:08.670 --> 00:50:11.610
I was having an argument
with him one day.

00:50:11.610 --> 00:50:18.500
I said, Fritz, Blue
Moon's a big brand.

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:22.330
He said, Steve, it doesn't
move the needle for us.

00:50:22.330 --> 00:50:24.420
It doesn't matter.

00:50:24.420 --> 00:50:28.210
And that's kind of the
way they look at things.

00:50:28.210 --> 00:50:36.680
AB InBev last year sold
323 million barrels of beer

00:50:36.680 --> 00:50:39.070
worldwide.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:46.390
SAB Miller sold 210 million,
Molson Coors sold 51 million.

00:50:46.390 --> 00:50:50.920
The whole craft beer segment
is about 20 million barrels.

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:53.730
So we have a long,
long way to go,

00:50:53.730 --> 00:50:56.220
and I think there are going
to be many years of growth.

00:50:56.220 --> 00:50:59.980
And I think the most
successful companies are

00:50:59.980 --> 00:51:02.660
going to be the ones
that stay independent,

00:51:02.660 --> 00:51:05.120
and that's what were
determined to do.

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:08.677
My business partners will
be the next generation

00:51:08.677 --> 00:51:09.510
of Brooklyn Brewery.

00:51:09.510 --> 00:51:11.022
We're not going to sell out.

00:51:11.022 --> 00:51:11.980
AUDIENCE: Good to hear.

00:51:14.692 --> 00:51:16.050
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:16.050 --> 00:51:18.772
Thanks for coming,
appreciate the talk a lot.

00:51:18.772 --> 00:51:22.910
I had the good fortunes
of being in Denmark

00:51:22.910 --> 00:51:25.265
earlier this year,
and really had

00:51:25.265 --> 00:51:27.570
a blast at Mikkeller
&amp; Friends and tasted

00:51:27.570 --> 00:51:28.680
some phenomenal stuff.

00:51:28.680 --> 00:51:31.835
I just wanted to get your
view on internationally,

00:51:31.835 --> 00:51:32.969
what's the place to watch?

00:51:32.969 --> 00:51:34.719
Where do you think a
lot of the cool stuff

00:51:34.719 --> 00:51:38.000
is happening outside the US?

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:43.140
STEVE HINDY: Well,
we're, I think,

00:51:43.140 --> 00:51:46.020
the biggest exporter
of craft beer.

00:51:46.020 --> 00:51:53.890
Last year, of our 220,000
barrels, about 28% was export.

00:51:53.890 --> 00:52:00.660
And our biggest markets
are Scandinavia and the UK.

00:52:00.660 --> 00:52:03.240
We're doing really
well in France.

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:05.210
It's beginning to
happen in Brazil

00:52:05.210 --> 00:52:08.040
in a big way, and Australia.

00:52:08.040 --> 00:52:12.900
And we just opened a brewery
in Stockholm with Carlsberg.

00:52:12.900 --> 00:52:14.850
It's a partnership
called New Carnegie

00:52:14.850 --> 00:52:16.850
Brewery by Brooklyn Brewery.

00:52:16.850 --> 00:52:19.340
If you go to Stockholm
you have to go visit.

00:52:19.340 --> 00:52:21.210
It's got a restaurant,
it's really cool.

00:52:21.210 --> 00:52:24.440
You can get there
by a ferry boat.

00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:30.340
So there's a lot of really cool
stuff happening in Scandinavia.

00:52:30.340 --> 00:52:34.760
We just did our Mash
Festival in London last week,

00:52:34.760 --> 00:52:37.480
and I was amazed.

00:52:37.480 --> 00:52:44.000
London now, there are 69
craft breweries in London.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.540
When I was in London in
the '90s when we first

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:51.280
started selling there, most
of the bars were tied houses.

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:53.720
So they're controlled
by the breweries.

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:56.340
There were only a handful
of free houses, which

00:52:56.340 --> 00:53:00.350
is a bar that can buy from
anybody that want to buy from.

00:53:00.350 --> 00:53:04.120
Now there are
countless free houses,

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:07.220
and they're carrying American
craft beer and British craft

00:53:07.220 --> 00:53:08.000
beer.

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:11.490
And a lot of the tide
houses are buying their way

00:53:11.490 --> 00:53:14.400
out of the relationships they
have with the big breweries

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:16.780
so they can carry craft beers.

00:53:16.780 --> 00:53:20.410
So we did an event at the
Camden Town Brewery, which

00:53:20.410 --> 00:53:23.710
is, I think Meantime
in Camden are

00:53:23.710 --> 00:53:28.900
the two biggest among
the London breweries.

00:53:28.900 --> 00:53:32.880
You've got to go see this
place is if you're in London.

00:53:32.880 --> 00:53:36.950
A lot of the breweries are done
where the cheapest rent is, not

00:53:36.950 --> 00:53:37.920
surprised.

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:42.200
They're done in these arches
under the rail trestles.

00:53:44.790 --> 00:53:46.710
Camden is unbelievable.

00:53:46.710 --> 00:53:49.450
They have eight arches.

00:53:49.450 --> 00:53:51.650
A lot of the arches
you can't connect them

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:53.100
because they're structural.

00:53:53.100 --> 00:53:54.520
But Camden, you can.

00:53:54.520 --> 00:53:56.260
So they have all these arches.

00:53:56.260 --> 00:54:01.310
They have fermenters
out in this alley kind

00:54:01.310 --> 00:54:05.510
of under the catwalks
for the trains.

00:54:05.510 --> 00:54:08.580
I don't know how they ever
got approval for this.

00:54:08.580 --> 00:54:09.960
And actually, the
guy from Camden

00:54:09.960 --> 00:54:13.170
said, well, what they
don't know won't hurt them.

00:54:13.170 --> 00:54:16.590
And across the street now,
there are apartment buildings.

00:54:16.590 --> 00:54:19.390
But when they opened,
it's kind of like what

00:54:19.390 --> 00:54:21.270
happened to us in Brooklyn.

00:54:21.270 --> 00:54:23.910
When they opened there
was nothing there.

00:54:23.910 --> 00:54:28.330
It was like a big, empty
lot across the street.

00:54:28.330 --> 00:54:32.250
So I think there's really
cool stuff happening

00:54:32.250 --> 00:54:35.920
in Denmark, in
Sweden, in Norway.

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:38.990
It's going to happen everywhere.

00:54:38.990 --> 00:54:41.050
And I'm sure the
Brazilians will come up

00:54:41.050 --> 00:54:46.970
with a lot besides ant beer.

00:54:46.970 --> 00:54:48.840
Yes?

00:54:48.840 --> 00:54:50.680
AUDIENCE: Hey, thank
so much for coming out.

00:54:50.680 --> 00:54:53.572
Just a quick question regarding
actually the Reddit AMA thread.

00:54:53.572 --> 00:54:57.234
I read through that, and your
number one piece of life advice

00:54:57.234 --> 00:54:58.775
was, don't do business
with assholes.

00:54:58.775 --> 00:54:59.150
STEVE HINDY: Yeah.

00:54:59.150 --> 00:55:01.370
AUDIENCE: Followed up by a
couple separation agreements,

00:55:01.370 --> 00:55:01.983
and stuff.

00:55:01.983 --> 00:55:04.529
Is there personal
anecdotes or situations

00:55:04.529 --> 00:55:07.076
that happened that made
this your number one

00:55:07.076 --> 00:55:09.990
piece of life advice?

00:55:09.990 --> 00:55:15.032
STEVE HINDY: Well, with Reddit
you've got to be on it, right?

00:55:15.032 --> 00:55:15.531
Yeah.

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:22.574
Milton Glaser is my designer.

00:55:22.574 --> 00:55:24.490
Milton's the guy who did
the "I love New York"

00:55:24.490 --> 00:55:27.740
logo, very wise man.

00:55:27.740 --> 00:55:30.060
Milton's 85 years old now.

00:55:30.060 --> 00:55:33.040
We've been working
together for 30 years.

00:55:33.040 --> 00:55:38.180
And Milton is the one
who basically gave me

00:55:38.180 --> 00:55:42.440
that bit of advice
many, many years ago.

00:55:42.440 --> 00:55:48.750
Because he doesn't design
for people he doesn't like.

00:55:48.750 --> 00:55:52.500
And it's been
pretty good advice.

00:55:52.500 --> 00:55:56.100
There have been cases
where we have done business

00:55:56.100 --> 00:55:58.220
with people who we
didn't really like,

00:55:58.220 --> 00:56:01.600
and usually it ends badly.

00:56:01.600 --> 00:56:07.370
Like there are a
lot of big retailers

00:56:07.370 --> 00:56:11.890
who basically will
say to me, look,

00:56:11.890 --> 00:56:15.400
I'll pay you this for your beer.

00:56:15.400 --> 00:56:20.770
Like your keg price is $100,
we're going to pay $75.

00:56:20.770 --> 00:56:23.680
And your face, you
know that you're

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:26.980
selling to hundreds
of people for $100,

00:56:26.980 --> 00:56:30.370
and here's this jerk
telling you, no, I'm

00:56:30.370 --> 00:56:32.050
going to buy for $75.

00:56:32.050 --> 00:56:34.860
And your best customers
are paying the full price.

00:56:34.860 --> 00:56:38.090
Now, a lot of brewers will
deal with people like that.

00:56:38.090 --> 00:56:39.690
I don't.

00:56:39.690 --> 00:56:43.680
I couldn't live with myself
if I'm selling to my better

00:56:43.680 --> 00:56:45.640
customers at this
higher price and I'm

00:56:45.640 --> 00:56:48.560
giving this jerk
a price for $75.

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:50.870
And I've seen it happen.

00:56:50.870 --> 00:56:52.840
It doesn't pay off
in the long run.

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:55.610
So anyway, not to get
carried away with that,

00:56:55.610 --> 00:56:58.630
I think it's pretty good advice.

00:56:58.630 --> 00:57:02.557
Maybe unavoidable
sometimes, but-- yeah?

00:57:02.557 --> 00:57:03.390
AUDIENCE: Hey there.

00:57:03.390 --> 00:57:05.115
Thanks for coming in.

00:57:05.115 --> 00:57:09.220
I actually had a follow up
question on one of early ones,

00:57:09.220 --> 00:57:13.320
breweries were using areas
where the rent's fairly low.

00:57:13.320 --> 00:57:14.384
STEVE HINDY: With what?

00:57:14.384 --> 00:57:15.800
AUDIENCE: How
breweries tend to go

00:57:15.800 --> 00:57:17.940
for areas with the
really low rents.

00:57:17.940 --> 00:57:20.404
STEVE HINDY: Yeah.

00:57:20.404 --> 00:57:21.820
AUDIENCE: I think
my parents would

00:57:21.820 --> 00:57:24.140
be worried for me if I
started a brewery there.

00:57:24.140 --> 00:57:26.098
Do you know people, does
it usually work out OK

00:57:26.098 --> 00:57:29.040
for the brewers?

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:29.970
STEVE HINDY: Well.

00:57:29.970 --> 00:57:33.640
our first warehouse
was in Bushwick

00:57:33.640 --> 00:57:39.170
off Bushwick avenue one Meserole
in an old brewery building.

00:57:39.170 --> 00:57:44.550
And truck drivers would not
come in there after dark,

00:57:44.550 --> 00:57:47.190
these big truck
drivers would call in

00:57:47.190 --> 00:57:48.940
and say, we'll be
there in the morning.

00:57:48.940 --> 00:57:51.860
We're not coming this afternoon.

00:57:51.860 --> 00:57:56.300
And most mornings when
we came in to open up,

00:57:56.300 --> 00:57:59.550
there were junkies across the
street in this little needle

00:57:59.550 --> 00:58:00.950
park.

00:58:00.950 --> 00:58:10.450
But I had been in Beirut and
Baghdad, so I could handle it.

00:58:10.450 --> 00:58:12.650
But it's true.

00:58:12.650 --> 00:58:16.470
All the craft
brewers in London are

00:58:16.470 --> 00:58:18.990
in very dicey kind
of neighborhoods.

00:58:18.990 --> 00:58:22.820
I did an event in DC, part
of our Mash thing recently,

00:58:22.820 --> 00:58:26.200
and it was in a really
skeezy part of the DC.

00:58:26.200 --> 00:58:29.250
So that's kind of the way it is.

00:58:29.250 --> 00:58:31.850
You're manufacturing,
you can't afford

00:58:31.850 --> 00:58:35.350
to pay $20 a foot for your rent.

00:58:35.350 --> 00:58:37.480
You've got to go
where it's $3 a foot.

00:58:41.460 --> 00:58:43.150
But my parents were
thrilled that I

00:58:43.150 --> 00:58:47.340
had come back to the USA.

00:58:47.340 --> 00:58:52.030
Actually, my father did
not understand or believe

00:58:52.030 --> 00:58:53.220
in journalism.

00:58:53.220 --> 00:58:56.780
He was thrilled when I said
I'm going into business.

00:58:56.780 --> 00:58:57.800
It was like, finally!

00:58:57.800 --> 00:58:59.800
You'll make some money
with that Cornell degree.

00:59:03.577 --> 00:59:04.410
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:59:04.410 --> 00:59:06.690
STEVE HINDY: You're welcome.

00:59:06.690 --> 00:59:07.940
Well, thank you all very much.

00:59:07.940 --> 00:59:10.860
I'd be happy to sign
some books if you want.

00:59:10.860 --> 00:59:15.990
And if you have further
questions, have a nice day.

00:59:15.990 --> 00:59:18.370
Do you want to know
about the beers?

00:59:18.370 --> 00:59:19.680
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:22.690
STEVE HINDY: So that wheat beer,
Brooklyn Green Market Wheat,

00:59:22.690 --> 00:59:27.100
we do that with the GrowNYC,
the not for profit company that

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:32.030
runs all the 53 farmers
markets in New York City.

00:59:32.030 --> 00:59:36.690
And it's made with
70% local ingredients.

00:59:36.690 --> 00:59:39.630
So the grain is grown
in upstate New York.

00:59:39.630 --> 00:59:43.580
There's some barley from
Massachusetts in that beer.

00:59:43.580 --> 00:59:47.640
And we're committed
to growing that brand.

00:59:47.640 --> 00:59:52.190
So we had a wheat beer called
Brooklyner Weisse which

00:59:52.190 --> 00:59:56.250
we got rid of, and that's
our main wheat beer now.

00:59:56.250 --> 01:00:01.650
And part of the proceeds
goes to the GrowNYC

01:00:01.650 --> 01:00:05.620
of every bottle we
sell of that beer.

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:07.430
And they sell it at
the green markets,

01:00:07.430 --> 01:00:10.600
and they make all the
retail markup on that.

01:00:10.600 --> 01:00:15.240
So it's our way of
supporting farmers,

01:00:15.240 --> 01:00:18.130
and we're hoping
the farmers upstate

01:00:18.130 --> 01:00:19.900
are going to grow
more grain every year

01:00:19.900 --> 01:00:21.850
so we can produce
more of this beer

01:00:21.850 --> 01:00:25.480
and take it beyond
New York state.

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:29.300
The other beer,
Brooklyn Cuvee Noir,

01:00:29.300 --> 01:00:33.180
is a strong stout that we
age in bourbon barrels.

01:00:33.180 --> 01:00:36.210
It's also got a little
sweet orange peel in it.

01:00:36.210 --> 01:00:39.060
It's aged in bourbon barrels
for more than six months,

01:00:39.060 --> 01:00:41.270
and it's part of our
barrel age series.

01:00:41.270 --> 01:00:46.350
Every quarter we have a
different bottled beer

01:00:46.350 --> 01:00:51.750
that's aged in bourbon barrels,
or wine barrels, or whatever.

01:00:51.750 --> 01:00:56.986
I think the last one was Wild
Streak, which is basically

01:00:56.986 --> 01:01:02.010
a version of a local one
aged in bourbon barrels

01:01:02.010 --> 01:01:04.570
and finished off with
